l, Scotland":"Lochawe, Argyll, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Dundee","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from the city of Dundee in Angus, Scotland."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Mariot","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["pet form of   Marguerite  , now used as an independent given name. In England it is still usually pronounced in the French way, but in Eastern Europe the final consonant is sounded, and this has had some influence in America."],"variants":[{"name":"Margaux","meanings":["Fanciful respelling of   Margot  , inspired by a village near Bordeaux noted for its red wine."]},{"name":"Margo","meanings":["pet form of   Marguerite  , now used as an independent given name. In England it is still usually pronounced in the French way, but in Eastern Europe the final consonant is sounded, and this has had some influence in America."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Mariot Margaret de Dundee was born about 1290, in Glassary, Argyll, Scotland, her father, Radulph de Dundee, was 36 and her mother, Isabella MacGilchrist, was 17. She married Sir Dougal Campbell - Laird of Auchinbreck before 1330, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1340, in Lochawe, Argyll, Scotland, at the age of 51, and was buried in Lochawe, Argyll, Scotland."},"et":{"about 1290–1340":"umbes 1290–1340","1290–1340":"1290–1340","1292–1330":"1292–1330","1312–1333":"1312–1333","1330–1380":"1330–1380","1255–1307":"1255–1307","1275–1310":"1275–1310","about 1290":"umbes 1290","before 1330":"enne 1330","1330":"1330","1275":"1275","1340":"1340","1380":"1380","1292":"1292","1290":"1290","1312":"1312","1333":"1333","1310":"1310","1255":"1255","about 1310":"umbes 1310","1307":"1307","Glassary, Argyll, Scotland":"Glassary, Argyll, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Lochawe, Argyll, Sc